      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Battle for Control Of the Runways</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Roger J Cohen letter says Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's fulminations about New York City's airports will come to nothing because city has huge backlog of critical infrastructure needs and will be hard-pressed to come up with money for airports (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mayor Presses Port Authority for Control of Airports'' (news article, Jan. 10):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mayor Presses Port Authority for Control of Airports'' (news article, Jan. 10):</p>
        <p>In the 1940's, Fiorello La Guardia and Robert Moses formed an unlikely alliance with the aim of developing modern airports for New York City. The authority they set up foundered  because the city's capital capacity proved insufficient. The task fell to the bi-state Port of New York Authority, which summoned the resources needed to develop the largest regional airport system on earth.</p>
        <p>Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's fulminations regarding a city takeover of Kennedy and La Guardia Airports break down for the same reasons La Guardia and Moses failed. With New York's huge backlog of critical infrastructure needs, the city will be hard pressed to come up with adequate capital for the airports' continuing renewal programs.</p>
        <p>ROGER J. COHEN  New York, Jan. 11, 2001</p>
        <p>The writer was assistant director of the Port Authority's office of economic and policy analysis, 1992-96.</p>
      </block>
